│ log shows \"Erasing scalar: %cmp80.1.2.i.i193 = icmp sgt i32 0, 0\"         │
│ followed by the assertion failure. The issue is that while the vectorizer   │
│ replaces some uses with poison values, it doesn't handle all users          │
│ correctly.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis: Looking at the code in                │
│ `HorizontalReduction::tryToReduce`, specifically around lines 19664-19680,  │
│ we see that the code attempts to replace uses of instructions being deleted │
│ with poison values. However, the condition on line 19674 only replaces uses │
│ if the instruction is not already use_empty(). This misses the case where   │
│ an instruction might have users that are not in the IgnoreSet but should    │
│ still be handled. More critically, the replacement with poison values       │
│ happens after the assertion check in `removeInstructionsAndOperands`,       │
│ creating a race condition where the assertion sees the old users before     │
│ they're replaced.\n\nThe real issue is that the code assumes that after     │
│ calling `ReductionRoot->replaceAllUsesWith(VectorizedTree)` on line 19653,  │
│ all remaining users of the scalar instructions are internal to the          │
│ reduction tree and can be safely replaced with poison. However, in this     │
│ specific case with boolean logic operations and selects, there are users    │
│ that aren't properly accounted for in the IgnoreSet or aren't being         │
│ replaced before the deletion attempt.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s): The fix │
│ is to ensure that all uses of instructions being deleted are properly       │
│ replaced with poison values BEFORE calling `removeInstructionsAndOperands`. │
│ The current code at lines 19674-19677 only replaces uses if the instruction │
│ is not use_empty(), but we need to ensure this replacement happens          │
│ unconditionally for all instructions in RdxOps that have users outside the  │
│ normal vectorization flow.\n\nHowever, looking more carefully at the code   │
│ structure, the actual issue is that the replacement logic is correct, but   │
│ the problem is that some users are not being recognized as part of the      │
│ reduction tree. The better fix is to move the poison replacement logic to   │
│ happen before any deletion attempts, ensuring that by the time we reach     │
│ `removeInstructionsAndOperands`, all instructions truly have no external    │
│ users.\n\nLooking at the exact location, the issue is in the loop at lines  │
│ 19664-19680. The current code replaces uses with poison values but only     │
│ after checking if the instruction has uses. We need to ensure this          │
│ replacement happens for all instructions that might have users, regardless  │
│ of the use_empty() check.\n\n5. Conclusion: The edit point at lines         │
│ 19674-19677 ensures that all instructions being deleted have their uses     │
│ properly replaced with poison values before the deletion assertion is       │
│ checked. This prevents the assertion failure by ensuring that by the time   │
│ `removeInstructionsAndOperands` is called, all instructions either have no  │
│ uses or only have uses from instructions that are also being deleted."})    │
