│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                 │
│                                                                             │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                             │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue: The assertion failure occurs in                 │
│ `removeInstructionsAndOperands` when trying to erase instructions that      │
│ still have users. The assertion checks that either an instruction has no    │
│ uses or all its users have been marked as deleted. In this case, the        │
│ instruction `%cmp80.1.2.i.i193` (and others in the DeadVals array) still    │
│ has users that haven't been properly handled before deletion.               │
│                                                                             │
│ 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log: The debug log shows that the SLP vectorizer is    │
│ attempting to vectorize a horizontal reduction. It successfully creates     │
│ vectorized versions of compare instructions but fails during cleanup. The   │
│ log shows "Erasing scalar: %cmp80.1.2.i.i193 = icmp sgt i32 0, 0" followed  │
│ by the assertion failure. The issue is that while the vectorizer replaces   │
│ some uses with poison values, it doesn't handle all users correctly.        │
│                                                                             │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis: Looking at the code in                              │
│ `HorizontalReduction::tryToReduce`, specifically around lines 19664-19680,  │
│ we see that the code attempts to replace uses of instructions being deleted │
│ with poison values. However, the condition on line 19674 only replaces uses │
│ if the instruction is not already use_empty(). This misses the case where   │
│ an instruction might have users that are not in the IgnoreSet but should    │
│ still be handled. More critically, the replacement with poison values       │
│ happens after the assertion check in `removeInstructionsAndOperands`,       │
│ creating a race condition where the assertion sees the old users before     │
│ they're replaced.                                                           │
│                                                                             │
│ The real issue is that the code assumes that after calling                  │
│ `ReductionRoot->replaceAllUsesWith(VectorizedTree)` on line 19653, all      │
│ remaining users of the scalar instructions are internal to the reduction    │
│ tree and can be safely replaced with poison. However, in this specific case │
│ with boolean logic operations and selects, there are users that aren't      │
│ properly accounted for in the IgnoreSet or aren't being replaced before the │
│ deletion attempt.                                                           │
│                                                                             │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s): The fix is to ensure that all uses of            │
│ instructions being deleted are properly replaced with poison values BEFORE  │
│ calling `removeInstructionsAndOperands`. The current code at lines          │
│ 19674-19677 only replaces uses if the instruction is not use_empty(), but   │
│ we need to ensure this replacement happens unconditionally for all          │
│ instructions in RdxOps that have users outside the normal vectorization     │
│ flow.                                                                       │
│                                                                             │
│ However, looking more carefully at the code structure, the actual issue is  │
│ that the replacement logic is correct, but the problem is that some users   │
│ are not being recognized as part of the reduction tree. The better fix is   │
│ to move the poison replacement logic to happen before any deletion          │
│ attempts, ensuring that by the time we reach                                │
│ `removeInstructionsAndOperands`, all instructions truly have no external    │
│ users.                                                                      │
│                                                                             │
│ Looking at the exact location, the issue is in the loop at lines            │
│ 19664-19680. The current code replaces uses with poison values but only     │
│ after checking if the instruction has uses. We need to ensure this          │
│ replacement happens for all instructions that might have users, regardless  │
│ of the use_empty() check.                                                   │
│                                                                             │
│ 5. Conclusion: The edit point at lines 19674-19677 ensures that all         │
│ instructions being deleted have their uses properly replaced with poison    │
│ values before the deletion assertion is checked. This prevents the          │
│ assertion failure by ensuring that by the time                              │
│ `removeInstructionsAndOperands` is called, all instructions either have no  │
│ uses or only have uses from instructions that are also being deleted.       │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                             │
